Lachmann enumeratos seven MSS. which he considers more or less authentic; and Hertzberg has given the readings of that number in his recent edition. But there are in fact only two, or at most three, which can claim to be wholly or nearly free from conjectural interpolations. The oldest is the Naples MS, already mentioned, of the thirteenth century ε but the best is generally considered to be the Codex Groninganus, (at Groningen, in Holland,) though its readings, which sometimes differ from all others, are oocasionally suspicious. The third is the Hamburg MS, of which Hertzberg has given for the first time a complete and accurate collation. It isnot earlier

than the fifteenth century, but, though full of errors and mis-spelt names, is apparently derived from a good source, · and has not been tempered with by the transcriber.‡
